239
00:11:22.882 --> 00:11:25.147
- I hope you like iced lattes.
- Thank you.

240
00:11:26.653 --> 00:11:29.213
I am so sorry for the
cryptic messages. I just...

241
00:11:29.289 --> 00:11:30.882
I really needed to talk to you.

242
00:11:31.691 --> 00:11:35.253
Look. I could just tell that you're
not like all of Sasha's other girlfriends.

243
00:11:35.328 --> 00:11:37.388
You're like a real human being.

244
00:11:37.630 --> 00:11:40.862
You're not just trying to get
close to him because he's famous.

245
00:11:41.434 --> 00:11:44.768
And I can tell he's really
crazy about you. so...

246
00:11:46.139 --> 00:11:48.131
Has he told you
about my mother at all?

247
00:11:48.775 --> 00:11:50.368
Um. a little. Yeah.

248
00:11:50.443 --> 00:11:52.378
He told you she
was an addict. right?

249
00:11:53.880 --> 00:11:56.941
Has he told you that he's
the one who got her hooked?

250
00:12:00.386 --> 00:12:01.386
No.

251
00:12:02.689 --> 00:12:05.386
Or how about the fact
that she was the one

252
00:12:05.458 --> 00:12:07.393
who supported the two of them

253
00:12:07.627 --> 00:12:09.823
for an entire decade at
the beginning of his career?

254
00:12:10.196 --> 00:12:11.316
- Did he tell you that?
- No.

255
00:12:11.364 --> 00:12:13.458
Um. I don't know.
but I'm sorry. I didn't...

256
00:12:13.533 --> 00:12:15.627
What-what does this
have to do with me exactly?

257
00:12:17.437 --> 00:12:18.735
She left me money.

258
00:12:18.972 --> 00:12:23.467
My grandparents were rich.
and Sasha's in charge of it.

259
00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:27.272
He's supposed to pay me an
income every year. but he never does.

260
00:12:27.347 --> 00:12:30.647
I mean. I have to practically squat
at his house to get him to pay me.

261
00:12:30.717 --> 00:12:33.448
That money that you were
asking for is your money?

262
00:12:34.988 --> 00:12:38.755
- Well. why would he do that?
- I had a bad couple of years.

263
00:12:39.025 --> 00:12:43.053
I fucked up a bit. I...
tried committing suicide.

264
00:12:43.129 --> 00:12:44.929
I mean. my mom had
just died. for fuck's sake.

265
00:12:45.965 --> 00:12:47.729
But all of that is
behind me now.

266
00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:50.998
I have an apartment.
I have two jobs.

267
00:12:51.070 --> 00:12:52.129
I'm writing a book.

268
00:12:52.372 --> 00:12:54.841
That's great. I mean.
it sounds really great.

269
00:12:54.907 --> 00:12:56.273
I want to terminate the trust.

270
00:12:57.143 --> 00:13:01.137
And I need your help getting
Sasha to listen to reason.

271
00:13:01.414 --> 00:13:02.609
I'll be 21 next month.

272
00:13:02.682 --> 00:13:04.651
I should be able to
control my own money.

273
00:13:04.717 --> 00:13:07.312
Why would he keep your
mother's money? He doesn't need it.

274
00:13:09.022 --> 00:13:10.022
[laughs softly]

275
00:13:10.456 --> 00:13:12.652
It's not about the money. Helen.

276
00:13:12.725 --> 00:13:14.318
It's about control.

277
00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:17.894
I mean. control me. and
he controls the story I tell.

278
00:13:18.531 --> 00:13:21.371
It's all about his image. That's the
only thing he actually cares about.

279
00:13:22.302 --> 00:13:23.793
[knocking on window]

280
00:13:24.837 --> 00:13:26.396
Oh. fuck.

281
00:13:26.773 --> 00:13:28.742
I've got to get back.
I can't lose this job.

282
00:13:29.309 --> 00:13:31.904
Look. can you just
talk to him for me?

283
00:13:32.879 --> 00:13:33.879
Please?

284
00:13:34.380 --> 00:13:35.473
Will you help me?

285
00:13:36.816 --> 00:13:37.943
I don't know.

286
00:13:38.818 --> 00:13:40.047
I'll think about it.

287
00:13:52.265 --> 00:13:54.325
Hey. You look great.
Do you feel better?

288
00:13:55.468 --> 00:13:57.300
- Uh. Mariel's here.
- Who?

289
00:13:57.370 --> 00:13:58.929
Mariel. my social worker.

290
00:13:59.339 --> 00:14:00.339
Oh.

291
00:14:01.374 --> 00:14:03.138
- Come in.
- Oh. okay.

292
00:14:09.649 --> 00:14:12.483
Can I get you anything.
Mariel? Tea or biscuits or...

293
00:14:12.552 --> 00:14:14.248
No. thanks. I'm all right.

294
00:14:17.857 --> 00:14:20.292
There we go. Okay.

295
00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:22.326
Where are you from?

296
00:14:22.562 --> 00:14:24.531
[Mariel] Los Angeles.
born and raised.

297
00:14:24.597 --> 00:14:27.260
Oh. me. too! California girls!

298
00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:30.067
Do you have any relatives
close by that you can rely on?

299
00:14:30.136 --> 00:14:32.503
Uh. yes. My mother is close by.

300
00:14:32.572 --> 00:14:33.652
Would you like some cheese?

301
00:14:33.773 --> 00:14:35.537
[Mariel] Uh. what is
your mother's name?

302
00:14:36.075 --> 00:14:38.237
Her name is. um. Adeline Taylor.

303
00:14:38.511 --> 00:14:40.605
[Mariel] And your mother
lives in Los Angeles?

304
00:14:40.713 --> 00:14:43.706
Uh. her primary residence
is Los Angeles. yes.

305
00:14:43.783 --> 00:14:45.060
- Um. but she's an actress...
- [Eddie crying]

306
00:14:45.084 --> 00:14:47.144
so she moves around
a lot... Hey. hey. hey.

307
00:14:47.220 --> 00:14:49.798
[Mariel] "Primary residence." Does
that mean she has multiple homes?

308
00:14:49.822 --> 00:14:50.983
[Sierra] It's okay. Yes.

309
00:14:51.124 --> 00:14:52.592
Yeah. Oh. my gosh.

310
00:14:53.126 --> 00:14:54.560
I'm so sorry about the racket.

311
00:14:54.627 --> 00:14:57.426
I totally forgot about
Eddie's sweet potatoes.

312
00:14:57.497 --> 00:14:59.159
I make all of his
food from scratch.

313
00:14:59.332 --> 00:15:02.268
It's okay. Just one sec. Okay.

314
00:15:03.569 --> 00:15:04.798
Ooh. Ooh. ooh. ooh.

315
00:15:04.871 --> 00:15:06.237
- Whoa.
- Hi.

316
00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:08.817
You have the instincts
of a panther. Helen.

317
00:15:08.841 --> 00:15:10.139
Lucky you were there.

318
00:15:10.810 --> 00:15:12.642
Are... [stutters]
you leaving already?

319
00:15:12.712 --> 00:15:14.840
Yes. I think I have
everything I need.

320
00:15:14.914 --> 00:15:16.625
You don't want to ask me
some more questions. or...

321
00:15:16.649 --> 00:15:17.844
Have a nice day.

322
00:15:18.518 --> 00:15:22.011
[Eddie cries]

323
00:15:22.655 --> 00:15:23.655
Um...

324
00:15:24.524 --> 00:15:25.423
- It's okay. Ooh.
- Whoopsie.

325
00:15:25.491 --> 00:15:27.426
- Hang on. hang on one second.
- [door closes]

326
00:15:28.895 --> 00:15:30.261
[Helen] Uh. excuse me.

327
00:15:30.830 --> 00:15:33.527
Ma'am. um. you're. uh...

328
00:15:33.599 --> 00:15:36.535
Mariel. um. can you tell
me what the next steps are?

329
00:15:36.602 --> 00:15:38.833
I'm sorry. I can't share that
with anyone but Ms. James.

330
00:15:38.905 --> 00:15:42.637
Okay. but hypothetically. if it
was an investigation like Sierra's.

331
00:15:42.708 --> 00:15:44.142
[stammers] what
would the next...

332
00:15:44.210 --> 00:15:45.210
Hypothetically.

333
00:15:45.278 --> 00:15:48.373
if the subject of an investigation
is found to be an unfit parent.

334
00:15:48.448 --> 00:15:50.159
the subject's child would
be removed from the home

335
00:15:50.183 --> 00:15:51.947
and placed with the next of kin.

336
00:15:52.852 --> 00:15:53.852
Like her mother?

337
00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:56.419
I really can't talk
about this anymore.

338
00:15:58.591 --> 00:16:01.493
[car door opens. closes]

339
00:16:01.861 --> 00:16:03.853
[engine starts]

340
00:16:03.930 --> 00:16:06.900
- [crying]
- [Helen] Sierra.

341
00:16:06.966 --> 00:16:09.401
- Sierra. it's okay.
- It's not. It's not.

342
00:16:09.469 --> 00:16:11.938
It's not. I can't
do anything right.

343
00:16:12.004 --> 00:16:14.633
- I'm gonna end up killing him.
- Oh. no. you're not.

344
00:16:14.707 --> 00:16:16.073
No. you're not.

345
00:16:16.342 --> 00:16:20.006
It was one mistake. I mean.
this period is... [stuttering]

346
00:16:20.480 --> 00:16:23.507
it's an adjustment. And
all mothers make mistakes.

347
00:16:23.583 --> 00:16:24.812
No. you don't understand.

348
00:16:24.884 --> 00:16:27.513
I can't get out of
bed in the morning.

349
00:16:29.355 --> 00:16:31.586
I just lay there staring
at the ceiling and I...

350
00:16:32.225 --> 00:16:35.218
I can't stop thinking. I
can't stop thinking about...

351
00:16:35.595 --> 00:16:38.588
hurting myself. and I just
want to leave him somewhere

352
00:16:38.664 --> 00:16:40.530
so that somebody
will find him and.

353
00:16:40.600 --> 00:16:42.711
and I think they should just
take him away from me now

354
00:16:42.735 --> 00:16:43.979
so that he doesn't
have to remember me.

355
00:16:44.003 --> 00:16:45.835
Oh. no. Shh.

356
00:16:45.938 --> 00:16:47.736
Oh. God. Sierra.

357
00:16:51.310 --> 00:16:53.609
- Listen to me. Will you listen to me?
- Mm-hmm.

358
00:16:53.679 --> 00:16:55.580
I think that you need
some help. okay?

359
00:16:57.350 --> 00:16:58.181
[sniffles]

360
00:16:58.251 --> 00:17:00.379
All right? You're not equipped
to do this on your own.

361
00:17:03.389 --> 00:17:05.949
How come everybody
can do this but me?

362
00:17:11.497 --> 00:17:14.228
I don't think that you should
be alone right now. Hmm?

363
00:17:15.568 --> 00:17:18.128
So why don't you and Eddie come
stay with me for a while? Hmm?

364
00:17:18.204 --> 00:17:19.570
- Okay.
- Okay.

365
00:17:19.639 --> 00:17:21.972
- Thank you.
- We'll get you some help.

366
00:17:29.282 --> 00:17:30.282
[coos]

367
00:17:32.418 --> 00:17:34.751
[suitcase wheels rolling]

368
00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:36.118
Surprise!

369
00:17:36.188 --> 00:17:37.417
Oh. Jesus Christ. wow.

370
00:17:37.490 --> 00:17:39.925
- Hey. [laughs]
- Hey. How you doing?

371
00:17:40.826 --> 00:17:42.738
I thought you were in the
Sahara? Or something...

372
00:17:42.762 --> 00:17:44.002
Well. production got shut down.

373
00:17:44.063 --> 00:17:47.465
I mean. uh. civil unrest
in Chad or something.

374
00:17:47.533 --> 00:17:48.944
Don't know. Whatever.
Doesn't matter.

375
00:17:48.968 --> 00:17:50.300
Can you pack a quick bag?

376
00:17:50.369 --> 00:17:52.169
Uh. we've got a jet
waiting for us at Van Nuys

377
00:17:52.438 --> 00:17:55.203
and a reservation at the
French Laundry in two hours.

378
00:17:55.374 --> 00:17:57.070
- Hi. How are you?
- Hi.

379
00:17:57.443 --> 00:17:59.776
I can't go to San Francisco.

380
00:18:00.212 --> 00:18:02.057
I mean. my kids are in there.
They're making me dinner.

381
00:18:02.081 --> 00:18:03.121
What the fuck do you mean?

382
00:18:03.583 --> 00:18:05.609
Helen. I flew 15
hours to surprise you.

383
00:18:05.685 --> 00:18:07.984
Have you got any idea
how hard it is to get a charter

384
00:18:08.054 --> 00:18:09.818
out of Chad during civil war?

385
00:18:10.256 --> 00:18:11.952
- No.
- Well. it's hard.

386
00:18:15.394 --> 00:18:17.488
I'm sorry. I can't.
I mean. I just...

387
00:18:17.997 --> 00:18:19.090
I can't. Sorry.

388
00:18:19.165 --> 00:18:21.794
[sighs] Well. whatever.
You just take these. then.

389
00:18:21.867 --> 00:18:24.063
Uh. it was supposed
to say "Happy Birthday."

390
00:18:24.136 --> 00:18:25.736
but. uh. somehow my
assistant fucked up.

391
00:18:25.805 --> 00:18:27.933
I mean. you're welcome
to come in and join us.

392
00:18:28.307 --> 00:18:32.574
Um. I mean. it's no French Laundry.
and we'll be with my kids and...

393
00:18:32.845 --> 00:18:33.845
But...

394
00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:35.480
[Sasha] Yeah.

395
00:18:35.915 --> 00:18:36.915
Love to.

396
00:18:37.750 --> 00:18:38.774
Yeah.

397
00:18:40.720 --> 00:18:41.720
Okay. cool.

398
00:18:44.090 --> 00:18:45.890
[Sasha] Um. you know.
I picked up a few tricks

399
00:18:45.925 --> 00:18:47.484
when I played a
chef some years back.

400
00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:50.758
- Do you want me to take over?
- I'm good.

401
00:18:50.863 --> 00:18:52.627
This is my dad's recipe.

402
00:18:52.698 --> 00:18:54.860
Oh. Your dad's.

403
00:18:57.737 --> 00:19:01.401
Mmm. Stacey. that's an
awful lot of sauce. isn't it?

404
00:19:01.707 --> 00:19:02.902
Nope. it's just right.

405
00:19:02.975 --> 00:19:05.342
Sasha. Let her do it.

406
00:19:06.212 --> 00:19:07.339
Yeah. sure.

407
00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:09.039
Sorry. Just trying to help.

408
00:19:12.385 --> 00:19:13.585
Are you sure you're all right?

409
00:19:13.853 --> 00:19:16.288
[Trevor] Oh. uh. Mom
hates her birthday.

410
00:19:16.622 --> 00:19:20.150
Yep. even when we were kids.
she wouldn't let us get her a cake.

411
00:19:20.726 --> 00:19:25.061
My dad would make a lasagna.
stick a candle in it. and that'd be it.

412
00:19:25.531 --> 00:19:26.531
Birthday finito.

413
00:19:27.967 --> 00:19:29.492
What a shock you left him.

414
00:19:31.737 --> 00:19:33.467
I didn't. actually. He left me.

415
00:19:33.939 --> 00:19:36.238
- [Sierra] Hello again.
- [Sasha] Hi.

416
00:19:36.509 --> 00:19:37.636
How's your baby?

417
00:19:38.077 --> 00:19:40.410
Uh. he's asleep. Thank God.

418
00:19:40.813 --> 00:19:43.009
[Sasha] See. that's
why I never had kids.

419
00:19:43.382 --> 00:19:46.216
I'm just absolutely
useless without my sleep.

420
00:19:48.521 --> 00:19:50.717
So. it's set in the future.

421
00:19:50.790 --> 00:19:54.352
Two astronauts meet by chance
on the International Space Station.

422
00:19:54.427 --> 00:19:57.761
They fall desperately in
love. but their love is doomed

423
00:19:57.897 --> 00:20:00.731
because they're being sent
off on two different missions

424
00:20:00.833 --> 00:20:04.998
in opposite directions
deep in the bowels of space.

425
00:20:05.838 --> 00:20:08.535
Quite the little
tragedian. isn't she?

426
00:20:09.508 --> 00:20:11.033
I wasn't finished.

427
00:20:11.744 --> 00:20:14.213
Anyways. they try
to forget each other.

428
00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:17.182
They build completely
new lives with new people.

429
00:20:17.249 --> 00:20:18.148
But it hurts. you know?

430
00:20:18.217 --> 00:20:21.483
Because deep down. they
secretly still love each other.

431
00:20:21.954 --> 00:20:25.721
Until one day. they run
into each other again

432
00:20:25.791 --> 00:20:28.260
on the opposite
side of the galaxy.

433
00:20:29.095 --> 00:20:30.188
Out in space?

434
00:20:30.629 --> 00:20:33.275
- That's very convenient. isn't it?
- [Stacey] Because all this time

435
00:20:33.299 --> 00:20:35.427
they thought they were
moving away from each other.

436
00:20:36.535 --> 00:20:38.231
they were actually in orbit.

437
00:20:38.704 --> 00:20:41.765
They were always
meant to meet again.

438
00:20:45.377 --> 00:20:46.640
I need more wine.

439
00:20:50.449 --> 00:20:53.476
I think it's a very
beautiful story. Stacey.

440
00:20:54.086 --> 00:20:55.086
Thanks.

441
00:20:55.421 --> 00:20:57.322
[knocking at door]

442
00:21:00.426 --> 00:21:02.190
- Hi.
- Hi.

443
00:21:02.261 --> 00:21:03.593
- Is Sierra here?
- Um...

444
00:21:03.662 --> 00:21:04.823
- Hi. babe.
- [Sierra] Mom?

445
00:21:04.897 --> 00:21:07.196
I'm so sorry to just
come over like this.

446
00:21:07.266 --> 00:21:11.727
but you're not answering your phone.
and this Mariel woman keeps calling me.

447
00:21:11.804 --> 00:21:13.500
She says she's
your social worker?

448
00:21:13.572 --> 00:21:16.269
- Hi. I'm Helen. I'm her neighbor.
- Oh. you're the neighbor.

449
00:21:16.342 --> 00:21:17.833
- Yeah. Hi.
- Right. right. Hi.

450
00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:18.741
Adeline Taylor.

451
00:21:18.811 --> 00:21:20.746
- It's so nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

452
00:21:20.813 --> 00:21:22.805
Sweetie. we got to
go. Can you get Eddie?

453
00:21:22.882 --> 00:21:24.475
Um. where are we going?

454
00:21:25.084 --> 00:21:26.279
Um. well.

455
00:21:26.385 --> 00:21:28.047
first. we're gonna
go back to my house.

456
00:21:28.120 --> 00:21:30.646
And I got a terrific
baby nurse for Eddie.

457
00:21:30.723 --> 00:21:32.443
And Dr. Miller says
he can take you tonight.

458
00:21:32.491 --> 00:21:34.824
No. Mom. please. I
don't want to go there.

459
00:21:34.894 --> 00:21:37.454
Honey. he's doing
us a tremendous favor.

460
00:21:37.530 --> 00:21:39.692
and it's all gonna be
very private. which is good.

461
00:21:39.765 --> 00:21:42.410
because if the press gets ahold
of this. they will have a field day.

462
00:21:42.434 --> 00:21:44.596
[Sierra] Mom. nobody
even knows who I am.

463
00:21:44.670 --> 00:21:47.333
Of course they do. sweetheart.
because they know who I am.

464
00:21:47.973 --> 00:21:51.375
But if we get ahead of
this. we can control it.

465
00:21:51.777 --> 00:21:52.777
All right?

466
00:21:52.978 --> 00:21:54.071
But we need to go tonight.

467
00:21:54.313 --> 00:21:55.440
Adeline?

468
00:21:57.316 --> 00:22:01.378
- Sasha Mann?
- What the fuck are you doing here?

469
00:22:03.455 --> 00:22:04.889
Sierra's my daughter.

470
00:22:05.391 --> 00:22:08.122
[Sasha] Fuck. no way.
You're. like. you're 35.

471
00:22:08.194 --> 00:22:09.194
[Adeline] I love you.

472
00:22:09.228 --> 00:22:10.924
Oh. what are you doing here?

473
00:22:10.996 --> 00:22:13.363
Well. I'm. um... Hey. I'm. uh...

474
00:22:13.432 --> 00:22:15.162
- I'm with. um...
- Helen.

475
00:22:15.234 --> 00:22:16.444
- I'm with Helen.
- Oh. thank God.

476
00:22:16.468 --> 00:22:18.164
For a second. thought
you were... [laughs]

477
00:22:18.237 --> 00:22:21.366
Well. okay. Cupid. Your
style's changing a bit.

478
00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:23.240
[Sasha] Hey. I haven't
seen you since. like...

479
00:22:23.475 --> 00:22:26.254
- Well. that press junket in Budapest...
- What are... What is she talking about?

480
00:22:26.278 --> 00:22:28.679
Um. she wants to
institutionalize me.

481
00:22:28.747 --> 00:22:31.911
- What?
- Yeah. Dr. Miller is. um...

482
00:22:32.151 --> 00:22:33.084
He works at a psych ward.

483
00:22:33.152 --> 00:22:35.986
She. um. she put me in
there when I was a teenager.

484
00:22:36.956 --> 00:22:38.667
[Sasha imitating French
accent] "The sun is rising.

485
00:22:38.691 --> 00:22:42.458
You have no dreams.
Your life is over. Action!"

486
00:22:43.829 --> 00:22:46.429
- [Adeline] It's so good to see you.
- [Sasha] So good to see you.

487
00:22:46.765 --> 00:22:48.597
Sierra. honey.
we really got to go.

488
00:22:50.369 --> 00:22:51.369
Honey?

489
00:22:53.072 --> 00:22:54.404
Yeah. I think...

490
00:22:54.473 --> 00:22:56.135
I know you've been
away for a few months.

491
00:22:56.208 --> 00:22:58.386
but I live next door. and we
spend quite a bit of time together.

492
00:22:58.410 --> 00:22:59.410
and I think...

493
00:23:00.779 --> 00:23:04.147
Sierra is suffering from
postpartum depression.

494
00:23:04.817 --> 00:23:08.083
- Are you a doctor?
- No.

495
00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:11.952
[chuckles] That's funny.
because you sounded like a doctor.

496
00:23:12.024 --> 00:23:14.926
Yeah. I just think she needs
some childcare. And a therapist.

497
00:23:14.994 --> 00:23:17.156
I don't think she needs
to be institutionalized.

498
00:23:17.229 --> 00:23:19.926
Institutionalized? I
mean. it's called rehab.

499
00:23:22.001 --> 00:23:25.130
If she's clean. we'll leave. If
she's not. it's the best place for her.

500
00:23:25.237 --> 00:23:27.502
Helen. perhaps we
should stay out of this.

501
00:23:27.573 --> 00:23:30.372
I mean. let the ladies sort it
themselves. It's not really...

502
00:23:30.442 --> 00:23:34.038
- It's none of our business. is it?
- Perhaps you should stay out of this.

503
00:23:37.716 --> 00:23:40.447
Um... [clicks tongue]

504
00:23:40.586 --> 00:23:43.522
Do you mind if I just talk to my
daughter privately for a moment?

505
00:23:56.568 --> 00:24:00.266
[Sasha] Look. all I'm saying is that this
is kind of your Achilles' heel. isn't it?

506
00:24:00.673 --> 00:24:03.905
I wish you would stop trying to turn me
wanting to help people into a pathology.

507
00:24:03.976 --> 00:24:05.968
Helen. her mother
is a movie star.

508
00:24:06.045 --> 00:24:08.344
She's got all the money
and resources in the world.

509
00:24:08.414 --> 00:24:10.414
Well. I know this might
be hard for you to believe.

510
00:24:10.482 --> 00:24:12.678
but sometimes people
need more than money

511
00:24:12.751 --> 00:24:15.277
- thrown at their problems.
- I just think you fill your life

512
00:24:15.354 --> 00:24:17.799
with other people's problems in
order to avoid addressing your own.

513
00:24:17.823 --> 00:24:19.257
That's all I'm saying.

514
00:24:19.325 --> 00:24:21.021
Do you think this is fun for me?

515
00:24:21.860 --> 00:24:23.338
Spending all this
time with the woman

516
00:24:23.362 --> 00:24:26.059
my boyfriend cheated
on me with and their baby?

517
00:24:26.165 --> 00:24:28.566
- Then why do you do it?
- Because she needs help.

518
00:24:29.068 --> 00:24:31.060
She's barely hanging on.

519
00:24:31.136 --> 00:24:35.096
Her mother is a psychopath.
I've tried to hate her. Believe me.

520
00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:37.732
But I ca... I can't.
She's just... She's too...

521
00:24:38.444 --> 00:24:39.844
pathetic to hate.

522
00:24:40.045 --> 00:24:43.072
Perhaps you do it
because you hate her.

523
00:24:44.383 --> 00:24:47.581
- What?
- Helen. people will go to crazy lengths

524
00:24:47.653 --> 00:24:49.349
to avoid feeling that feeling.

525
00:24:49.922 --> 00:24:51.390
All right. well...

526
00:24:52.825 --> 00:24:55.852
Speaking of people you hate.
guess who I had coffee with today.

527
00:24:57.429 --> 00:24:58.429
Christianna.

528
00:24:58.630 --> 00:25:01.395
- Christianna. Why?
- She reached out to me.

529
00:25:02.634 --> 00:25:03.829
But how'd she find you?

530
00:25:04.103 --> 00:25:06.214
- What does it matter?
- Well. you're kind of hard to track down.

531
00:25:06.238 --> 00:25:07.798
You're not on social
media or anything.

532
00:25:07.840 --> 00:25:10.571
- Why don't you want me to talk to her?
- Because why would you?

533
00:25:10.642 --> 00:25:12.873
She asked me for help
getting through to you.

534
00:25:13.112 --> 00:25:14.910
She says the money's hers.

535
00:25:14.980 --> 00:25:17.711
Oh. She told you about
Lily's trust. did she?

536
00:25:17.783 --> 00:25:18.876
- Yeah.
- Mm-hmm.

537
00:25:19.618 --> 00:25:21.211
Did she tell you
she's writing a book?

538
00:25:21.453 --> 00:25:22.512
I think so.

539
00:25:22.721 --> 00:25:23.984
Book about me?

540
00:25:25.591 --> 00:25:27.651
- No.
- Mm-hmm.

541
00:25:28.961 --> 00:25:32.454
Listen. I know she can be
very convincing. but she's lying.

542
00:25:32.531 --> 00:25:37.231
She's full of horseshit. I mean.
Lily and I loved each other. Helen.

543
00:25:37.803 --> 00:25:40.534
I met her when Christianna
was five. and I helped raise her.

544
00:25:40.606 --> 00:25:41.938
We were a family.

545
00:25:42.875 --> 00:25:46.141
But when Christianna became a
teenager. she got this asshole boyfriend

546
00:25:46.211 --> 00:25:48.043
that convinced her to
break into Lily's phone

547
00:25:48.113 --> 00:25:50.514
and steal these photos
of me and Lily naked.

548
00:25:50.582 --> 00:25:52.312
and Christianna
went and sold them.

549
00:25:52.518 --> 00:25:55.955
After that. Lily put a
stipulation in Christianna's trust

550
00:25:56.021 --> 00:25:58.991
that if she wanted her grandparents'
money when she was an adult.

551
00:25:59.058 --> 00:26:02.085
she could not disparage
me or Lily publicly.

552
00:26:02.327 --> 00:26:05.786
- And has she?
- No. not yet.

553
00:26:05.964 --> 00:26:10.095
But she's written this tell-all
book. and she wants to publish it.

554
00:26:10.636 --> 00:26:13.128
She gets her inheritance
in full when she's 25.

555
00:26:13.205 --> 00:26:15.504
which gives me four
years to change her mind.

556
00:26:17.109 --> 00:26:19.578
I mean. why... why did Lily
put you in charge of her trust?

557
00:26:19.645 --> 00:26:22.171
Because she trusted me. Helen.

558
00:26:23.115 --> 00:26:24.759
Christianna says you
never send the checks.

559
00:26:24.783 --> 00:26:27.014
Mm-hmm. because I
don't know where she lives.

560
00:26:27.419 --> 00:26:29.820
She's a grifter. She moves
around every six months.

561
00:26:29.888 --> 00:26:31.199
Why don't you just
give her the money

562
00:26:31.223 --> 00:26:33.101
and let her publish the book
if you have nothing to hide?

563
00:26:33.125 --> 00:26:34.616
For fuck's sake!

564
00:26:34.827 --> 00:26:36.693
That would ruin my career.

565
00:26:37.096 --> 00:26:40.794
I've worked too hard for too
long to throw my whole life away

566
00:26:40.866 --> 00:26:43.233
just because Christianna
is angry that her mother died

567
00:26:43.302 --> 00:26:44.770
and wants to blame
it on somebody.

568
00:26:44.837 --> 00:26:47.534
She says you got her
mother hooked on drugs.

569
00:26:47.606 --> 00:26:48.606
Are you f...

570
00:26:49.508 --> 00:26:51.136
Are you fucking kidding me?

571
00:26:55.013 --> 00:26:56.013
[exhales]

572
00:26:59.218 --> 00:27:02.780
Your ex-husband did a truly
amazing job of fucking you over.

573
00:27:03.589 --> 00:27:05.524
But if you don't
trust me by now.

574
00:27:06.658 --> 00:27:08.684
I don't know what
the fuck to tell you.

575
00:27:11.997 --> 00:27:14.057
[door slides open]

576
00:27:14.633 --> 00:27:16.226
[door slides closed]

577
00:27:16.301 --> 00:27:19.738
Sierra. honey. go get
Eddie. We're really late.

578
00:27:20.038 --> 00:27:21.165
What's going on?

579
00:27:22.374 --> 00:27:24.536
I'm gonna go and see Dr. Miller.

580
00:27:25.110 --> 00:27:28.911
and my mom is gonna take. uh.
care of Eddie while I get some help.

581
00:27:32.050 --> 00:27:34.542
Oh. Sierra. there has
to be some other option.

582
00:27:34.953 --> 00:27:37.047
No. I don't think so.

583
00:27:38.257 --> 00:27:39.257
What if I take him?

584
00:27:40.359 --> 00:27:42.021
- Helen.
- What?

585
00:27:42.895 --> 00:27:44.796
You can stay here
as long as you like.

586
00:27:44.863 --> 00:27:47.196
and I'll try to find someone
to come here and help you.

587
00:27:47.366 --> 00:27:48.493
What are you doing?

588
00:27:48.567 --> 00:27:52.004
She's his mother. I don't think
they should be separated right now.

589
00:27:52.371 --> 00:27:53.566
[exhales]

590
00:27:55.007 --> 00:27:55.872
Hey. I'm beat.

591
00:27:55.941 --> 00:27:57.534
I've been awake for 24 hours.

592
00:27:57.609 --> 00:28:00.204
so if you'll excuse me.

593
00:28:00.279 --> 00:28:03.010
- Um. Adeline. wonderful to see you.
- [Adeline] Mwah!

594
00:28:03.148 --> 00:28:06.585
- Call me. We'll have lunch or something.
- I will. We will. Bye.

595
00:28:11.089 --> 00:28:12.089
[Adeline sighs]

596
00:28:12.824 --> 00:28:15.851
I can tell you care
about my daughter.

597
00:28:16.695 --> 00:28:18.459
Many people do.

598
00:28:18.697 --> 00:28:22.190
She has a knack for finding
those people who want to save her.

599
00:28:23.669 --> 00:28:27.606
but then they just end up
enabling her addictions and laziness

600
00:28:27.673 --> 00:28:31.337
and her refusal to accept
any responsibility for her life.

601
00:28:32.611 --> 00:28:33.704
Excuse me?

602
00:28:33.912 --> 00:28:38.008
Oh. I'm sorry. I'm not saying
you're... one of those people.

603
00:28:38.083 --> 00:28:40.075
I don't know you.

604
00:28:40.352 --> 00:28:43.186
But I do know my daughter.

605
00:28:45.557 --> 00:28:48.459
She's sweet and beautiful.

606
00:28:48.627 --> 00:28:51.563
but she's also a fuck-up. and
she needs professional help.

607
00:28:52.831 --> 00:28:54.527
She doesn't need another...

608
00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:58.732
well-intentioned hanger-on.

609
00:28:59.204 --> 00:29:00.934
What the fuck is wrong with you?

610
00:29:03.242 --> 00:29:05.609
Why do you think I'm
such a fuck-up. Mom?

611
00:29:07.446 --> 00:29:08.914
Did you know that
until I met Helen.

612
00:29:08.981 --> 00:29:10.658
I didn't even realize there
were people in the world

613
00:29:10.682 --> 00:29:12.947
who loved their kids
just for being alive?

614
00:29:13.018 --> 00:29:15.317
Just because they
fucking existed?

615
00:29:15.988 --> 00:29:17.752
You should see
her with her kids.

616
00:29:18.090 --> 00:29:19.090
She's amazing.

617
00:29:19.391 --> 00:29:22.293
She loves them. She
just fucking loves them.

618
00:29:22.361 --> 00:29:25.263
They can fuck up or.
or say something stupid

619
00:29:25.330 --> 00:29:27.094
and it's like she
doesn't even notice.

620
00:29:28.467 --> 00:29:31.699
If I ever had a pimple on my
face. you couldn't even look at me.

621
00:29:31.870 --> 00:29:33.361
I stopped eating
because you said

622
00:29:33.438 --> 00:29:35.532
you'd rather have a dead
daughter than a fat one.

623
00:29:35.641 --> 00:29:38.338
- I was kidding.
- It wasn't fucking funny.

624
00:29:38.543 --> 00:29:41.206
- [sigh]
- Sierra] You didn't want a daughter.

625
00:29:41.546 --> 00:29:45.540
You just wanted a doll that you
could dress up and parade around

626
00:29:45.617 --> 00:29:46.995
and bring to interviews
when you needed

627
00:29:47.019 --> 00:29:50.512
- to seem more human.
- Oh. my God. Oh. my God. I tried so hard.

628
00:29:50.589 --> 00:29:52.319
My parents were useless.

629
00:29:52.391 --> 00:29:55.486
- Rich and famous and useless.
- Oh. my God.

630
00:29:55.560 --> 00:29:59.554
They had their assistant take me
to get my tonsils out when I was five.

631
00:30:00.165 --> 00:30:02.498
I did not want that
to be your childhood.

632
00:30:03.435 --> 00:30:04.926
I wanted you with me.

633
00:30:05.270 --> 00:30:07.796
[stuttering] I wanted
us to be in this together.

634
00:30:08.573 --> 00:30:09.851
You know. but I
guess I fucked up.

635
00:30:09.875 --> 00:30:13.437
I pushed you too hard or
I protected you too much.

636
00:30:13.512 --> 00:30:14.536
I don't know.

637
00:30:15.314 --> 00:30:18.307
I think I was just so
afraid of the scrutiny

638
00:30:18.383 --> 00:30:20.943
you were gonna be under
because you were my kid.

639
00:30:22.621 --> 00:30:24.487
It's a scary world. Sierra.

640
00:30:27.592 --> 00:30:32.030
The only thing that I'm scared
of. Mom. in the whole world.

641
00:30:32.097 --> 00:30:34.089
the whole entire world...

642
00:30:35.033 --> 00:30:36.057
is you.

643
00:30:44.743 --> 00:30:46.712
How do you two know
each other again?

644
00:30:49.581 --> 00:30:50.742
Don't do that. Mom.

645
00:30:51.283 --> 00:30:53.616
Oh. [sighs] Right.

646
00:30:55.220 --> 00:30:56.483
She...

647
00:30:57.489 --> 00:31:02.359
fucked your dying husband and
then got pregnant and had his baby?

648
00:31:03.929 --> 00:31:06.160
Well. technically. he
wasn't my husband.

649
00:31:07.632 --> 00:31:08.632
Mm-hmm.

650
00:31:09.368 --> 00:31:12.065
And you really feel you have
her best interests at heart.

651
00:31:15.407 --> 00:31:17.308
Life is short. Adeline.

652
00:31:19.644 --> 00:31:20.644
Okay.

653
00:31:22.447 --> 00:31:24.609
Sierra. I'll see you tomorrow.

654
00:31:26.017 --> 00:31:28.577
[footsteps leaving]

655
00:31:29.488 --> 00:31:30.488
[exhales]

656
00:31:31.423 --> 00:31:33.324
- [sighs]
- [door closes]

657
00:31:36.828 --> 00:31:37.828
[Sierra] Um...

658
00:31:39.331 --> 00:31:42.768
Do you mind if I just go
to bed? I'm... very tired.

659
00:31:42.834 --> 00:31:43.834
Of course.

660
00:31:46.171 --> 00:31:48.572
- Happy birthday.
- Thank you.

661
00:32:00.352 --> 00:32:01.820
[knocking at door]

662
00:32:10.262 --> 00:32:11.423
Happy birthday.

663
00:32:17.135 --> 00:32:19.013
[Noah] Well. I kind of like
the cover art they chose.

664
00:32:19.037 --> 00:32:23.099
It's. like. bare trees in a winter
wood. It's kind of haunting.

665
00:32:23.175 --> 00:32:24.438
It's a beautiful book. Noah.

666
00:32:24.509 --> 00:32:25.943
- It really is.
- Thanks. Thank you.

667
00:32:26.011 --> 00:32:27.171
And thank you for your blurb.

668
00:32:27.212 --> 00:32:29.408
- I'm really grateful.
- Ah. I loved reading it.

669
00:32:30.315 --> 00:32:32.750
[sighs] I'm sorry about
your mom. by the way.

670
00:32:33.218 --> 00:32:35.517
- That part was true. wasn't it?
- Mm-hmm.

671
00:32:35.887 --> 00:32:37.617
I had no idea back at school.

672
00:32:37.789 --> 00:32:39.018
Well. nobody did.

673
00:32:39.624 --> 00:32:42.958
You know what I find sort of
interesting. now that I'm getting older?

674
00:32:43.462 --> 00:32:45.988
All those people I thought were
so cool back when I was young?

675
00:32:46.064 --> 00:32:48.158
- Mm-hmm.
- Just effortlessly cool...

676
00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:50.935
Those people were
in so much pain.

677
00:32:51.503 --> 00:32:52.562
- You think?
- Ah.

678
00:32:52.704 --> 00:32:53.967
To a person.

679
00:32:54.172 --> 00:32:56.300
There's no such thing as
being cool when you're young.

680
00:32:56.374 --> 00:32:58.070
There's just different
degrees of terrified

681
00:32:58.143 --> 00:33:00.135
and how adept
you are at hiding it.

682
00:33:00.278 --> 00:33:02.941
Which is inversely
proportional. in my opinion.

683
00:33:03.048 --> 00:33:04.380
I love you. Ariel.

684
00:33:04.716 --> 00:33:05.979
I love you. too. Noah.

685
00:33:09.254 --> 00:33:12.088
It feels like things are finally
coming back together for you. huh?

686
00:33:14.626 --> 00:33:15.992
Hey. you want to get a coffee?

687
00:33:16.294 --> 00:33:17.728
- I'm buying.
- Sure.

688
00:33:24.903 --> 00:33:25.903
Can I ask you something?

689
00:33:27.272 --> 00:33:28.706
I got a call a
couple of days ago

690
00:33:28.773 --> 00:33:30.742
from a reporter who's
doing this long-form story

691
00:33:30.809 --> 00:33:33.108
about me and my "resurrection."

692
00:33:33.445 --> 00:33:34.445
Where? For what?

693
00:33:34.913 --> 00:33:36.108
<i>Vanity Fair.</i>

694
00:33:36.414 --> 00:33:37.541
- Wow.
- Mm.

695
00:33:37.649 --> 00:33:38.776
No. it's great. but...

696
00:33:39.718 --> 00:33:43.086
she asked me about this. uh.

697
00:33:43.288 --> 00:33:46.122
publicist I had on
the <i>Descent</i> tour...

698
00:33:46.858 --> 00:33:50.022
who. apparently.
has said that I...

699
00:33:50.729 --> 00:33:53.198
I don't know. tried to
seduce her or something.

700
00:33:53.965 --> 00:33:55.058
Tried to seduce her?

701
00:33:56.101 --> 00:33:57.592
Pressured her into
sleeping with me.

702
00:33:59.371 --> 00:34:00.371
That's different.

703
00:34:00.472 --> 00:34:02.373
I know... I know.

704
00:34:03.074 --> 00:34:06.074
I mean. I don't know what she meant.
but. I mean. she kind of blindsided me.

705
00:34:06.244 --> 00:34:08.189
- What did you say?
- Well. I told her it wasn't true.

706
00:34:08.213 --> 00:34:10.739
Which it wasn't.
The opposite. in fact.

707
00:34:11.016 --> 00:34:14.316
I mean. she was throwing
herself at me the whole time.

708
00:34:16.755 --> 00:34:19.133
- [chuckles] What. you don't believe me?
- [chuckles] I didn't say that.

709
00:34:19.157 --> 00:34:20.157
But you don't.

710
00:34:20.859 --> 00:34:23.055
I'm telling you. she was...
She was pretty aggressive.

711
00:34:23.862 --> 00:34:26.422
Okay. so what are
you worried about?

712
00:34:27.432 --> 00:34:30.561
Well. I don't know. Nothing.
I guess. It's probably fine.

713
00:34:31.603 --> 00:34:33.114
The reporter didn't seem
that interested. actually.

714
00:34:33.138 --> 00:34:36.666
She was probably just
doing due diligence. but...

715
00:34:39.144 --> 00:34:40.288
I mean. this publicist. Eden.

716
00:34:40.312 --> 00:34:42.281
she can't just make
shit up about me. right?

717
00:34:43.448 --> 00:34:46.816
You know you don't have the best
reputation around this stuff. right?

718
00:34:47.886 --> 00:34:49.797
Ariel. that was in college.
that was 30 years ago.

719
00:34:49.821 --> 00:34:50.831
That's not what
I'm talking about.

720
00:34:50.855 --> 00:34:53.825
I'm talking about your
current reputation. Noah.

721
